<h1>@HI{{suru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @EM{{@HI{{suru}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{suru}}}} is an important irregular Japanese verb that means "to cause a state or action"
and corresponds to "do" or "make".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{biru}}ha@KT{{hamuretto}}wo@EM{{suru}}tsumorida.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Bill is planning to play Hamlet.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{suru}}}} can mean "to wear" when used with small objects such as a watch or a tie.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ii@KT{{nekutai}}wo@EM{{shiteiru}}ne.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      You're wearing a nice tie, aren't you?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Compounds with @EM{{@HI{{suru}}}} form transitive words. In contemporary Japanese, @EM{{@HI{{suru}}}}
can be used with loanwords too.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{me}}hayoku@KJ{{car}}no@KJ{{carry^revolve}}wo@EM{{shimasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I often drive a car.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The idiomatic construction <a href="grammar-ni-suru.html">@N{{}}@HI{{nisuru}}</a> means "to decide on @N{{}}".
</p>

